  "prompt": "Strep b when pregnant?",
  "response": "Group B Streptococcus (GBS), also known as *Streptococcus agalactiae*, is a type of bacteria that can be found in the gastrointestinal tract, rectum, or vagina of about **10-30% of pregnant women**. While it is generally harmless in healthy adults, it can pose serious risks to newborns if transmitted during childbirth.\n\n### Key Points About GBS in Pregnancy:\n\n1. **Screening for GBS**:\n   - Pregnant women are typically screened for GBS between **35 and 37 weeks of gestation**.\n   - A swab is taken from the vagina and rectum to test for the presence of the bacteria.\n\n2. **GBS Positive Status**:\n   - If GBS is detected, it means you are *colonized* with the bacteria but not necessarily infected.\n   - Being GBS-positive does not mean you or your baby will definitely become ill, but precautions are taken to reduce the risk.\n\n3. **Risks to the Baby**:\n   - If GBS is passed to the baby during delivery, it can cause serious infections such as:\n     - **Early-onset GBS disease** (within the first week of life): pneumonia, sepsis, or meningitis.\n     - **Late-onset GBS disease** (up to several months after birth): less common but can still cause severe complications.\n\n4. **Prevention**:\n   - If you are GBS-positive, you will be given **intravenous (IV) antibiotics during labor** (usually penicillin or an alternative if allergic) to reduce the risk of transmitting the bacteria to your baby.\n   - Antibiotics are most effective when given at least **4 hours before delivery**.\n\n5. **Other Risk Factors**:\n   - If you have had a previous baby with GBS infection, you will automatically be treated during labor.\n   - Additional risk factors include preterm labor, fever during labor, or prolonged rupture of membranes.\n\n6. **If You Are GBS Positive**:\n   - Let your healthcare provider know as soon as labor starts.\n   - Follow their recommendations for monitoring and treatment.\n\n### Conclusion:\nBeing GBS-positive during pregnancy is common, and with proper screening and treatment, the risk to your baby is greatly reduced. Always discuss your test results and any concerns with your healthcare provider to ensure you and your baby receive the best care.",
